, 2018\n|[[Haridwar, Uttarakhand]], India\n| Student, 13\n| -\n|1 injured\n| DAV Public School shooting in Haridwar\n|-\n|February 11, 2019\n|[[Stowbtsy]], Belarus\n| Student, 15\n| 2 dead\n| 2 injured\n| A 15-year-old student stabbed a 50-year-old history teacher in the neck, who then died on the spot. He also stabbed two students, who tried to defend the teacher, injuring both of them. The assailant then left the class and entered a nearby classroom, where he stabbed a 17-year-old student, who also died on the spot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/belarusian-teen-suspected-of-stabbing-teacher-classmate-to-death/29763228.html|title=Belarusian Teen Suspected Of Stabbing Teacher, Classmate To Death |date=February 11, 2019 |work=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty}}</ref>\n|-\n|February 26, 2019\n|[[Toronto]], Ontario\n| Unknown\n| \n| 2 injured\n| A fight between two students ended off with a double stabbing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toronto.citynews.ca/2019/02/26/stabbing-york-memorial-collegiate/|title=2 students stabbed outside York Memorial Collegiate Institute |date=February 26, 2019 |work=CityNews}}</ref>\n|-\n|March 13, 2019\n|[[Suzano]], Brazil\n| Guilherme Taucci Monteiro, 17; Luiz Henrique de Castro, 25\n| 10 dead\n| 11 injured\n| [[Suzano massacre|Two masked]] men shot and killed 6 students and 2 staff members at a public secondary school in Suzano, Brazil. Eleven additional victims were wounded. The suspects committed suicide inside the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/13/americas/brazil-school-shooting/index.html/|title=At least 8 people were killed in a school shooting in Brazil |date=March 13, 2019 |work=CNN}}</ref>\n|-\n| May 7, 2019\n| Colorado, United States\n| Devon Erickson, 18; Maya Elizabeth, 16\n| 1 dead\n| 8 injured\n| At the [[STEM School Highlands Ranch]] two suspects, who were students at the school, injured eight students and killed one.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/08/us/denver-stem-shooting-heroes-run-hide-fight/index.html|title=Again in the age of 'run, hide, fight,' student heroes thwart a school shooter|first=Eliott C.|last= McLaughlin|website=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/08/us/kendrick-castillo-denver-stem-shooting/index.html|title=This student died trying to stop the Colorado school shooter|author1=Nicole Chavez |author2=Scott McLean|website=CNN}}</ref>\n|-\n| May 28, 2019\n| Volsk, Saratov Region, Russia\n| Daniil Pulkin\n| \n| 1 injured\n| In the afternoon of May 28, the teenager came to school with a bag containing an axe and molotov cocktails inside. First, Pulkin attempted to burn the office of his former form mistress. After that, he hit a 6th grader girl in the head with an axe.\n|-\n| August 8, 2019\n| Montgomery, Alabama\n| Isaiah Johnson, 38\n| 0\n| 0\n| 38-year old Isaiah Johnson dropped his son off at Blount Elementary School, and then got into an argument with another father over a traffic dispute. He then discharged a firearm into the other father's vehicle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvtm13.com/article/2-arrested-after-road-rage-shooting-at-alabama-elementary-school/28647302|title=Back-to-school traffic leads to argument, shooting outside Alabama elementary school|first=The Associated|last=Press|date=August 8, 2019|website=WVTM}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apr.org/post/mental-evaluation-sought-school-traffic-shooting-suspect|title=Mental evaluation sought for school traffic shooting suspect|first=Associated|last=Press|website=www.apr.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/crime/2019/08/26/isaiah-johnson-charged-escape-after-blount-elementary-shooting/2121409001/|title=Father charged in Blount Elementary shooting re-arrested after escaping treatment facility|first=Melissa|last=Brown|website=The Montgomery Advertiser}}</ref>\n|-\n| August 30, 2019\n| Mobile, Alabama\n| Deangelo Dejuan Parnell, 17\n| 0\n| 10 injured\n| Parnell shot 9 people during a confrontation at a stadium where a high school football game was being played. A tenth person suffered a stroke.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/31/us/mobile-alabama-football-shooting.html|title=At Least 10 Shot at Alabama High School Football Game, Police Say|first=Derrick Bryson|last=Taylor|date=August 31, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| October 1, 2019\n| [[Kuopio]], Finland\n| Joel Marin, 25\n| 1 dead\n| 10 injured\n| [[Kuopio school stabbing]]\n|-\n| November 14, 2019 \n| Santa Clarita, California\n| Nathaniel Berhow, 16\n| 3 dead\n| 3 injured \n| [[Saugus High School shooting]]\n|-\n| November 14, 2019\n| [[Blagoveshchensk]], Russia\n| Daniil Zasorin, 19\n| 2 dead\n| 3 injured\n| After being told to leave the classroom twice, Zasorin returned with a pump-action shotgun and opened fire in the room, shooting victims at their desks. He committed suicide after being wounded in exchange of gunfire with police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/russia-college-shooting-daniil-zasorin-attack-death-toll-latest-today-a9202526.html|title=Gunman opens fire in deadly Russian college attack after posting bizarre message online|date=14 November 2019|website=The Independent|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[School bullying]]\n*[[School shooting]]\n*[[List of school-related attacks]]\n*[[List of school shootings in the United States]]\n*[[List of attacks related to primary schools]]\n*[[List of attacks related to post-secondary schools]]\n*[[List of rampage killers: School massacres]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|refs=\n<ref name=note_a>Including death or injury of attacker(s), when applicable.</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181140/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence00-01.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2000\u20132001], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181216/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence02-03.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2002\u20132003], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181239/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence04-05.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2004\u20132005], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181347/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence06-07.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2006\u20132007], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181441/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence07-08.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2007\u20132008], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181632/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence08-09.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2008\u20132009], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181945/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence09-10.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2009\u20132010], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:School-Related Attacks}}\n[[Category:Attacks on schools|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of schools|*]]\n[[Category:Crime-related lists]]\n[[Category:Secondary education-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of school-related attacks|secondary]]\n", "name_user": "BorderRegions", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1960s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_attacks_related_to_secondary_schools"}
{"title_page": "Uncle Tom", "text_new": "{{short description|Title character of Uncle Tom's Cabin}}\n{{Infobox character\n| series             = [[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]\n| image              = ElizaEngraving cropped.jpg\n| caption            = Detail of an illustration from the first book edition of ''Uncle Tom's Cabin'', depicting Uncle Tom as young and muscular\n| first              = ''Uncle Tom's Cabin''\n| last               = ''Uncle Tom's Cabin''\n| creator            = [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]]\n| gender             = Male\n| nationality        = American\n}}\n{{Slavery}}\n'''Uncle Tom''' is the title character of [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]]'s 1852 novel, ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]''.<ref name=\"merriam-webster.com\">{{MerriamWebsterDictionary|Uncle Tom}}</ref> The character was seen by many readers as ground-breaking humanistic portrayal of an African-American slave, one who uses non-resistance and gives his life to protect others who have escaped from slavery. However, the character also came to be seen \u2013 especially based on his portrayal in pro-slavery dramatizations \u2013 as inappropriately subservient to white slaveholders. This led to the use of ''Uncle Tom'' \u2013 often shortened to just ''Tom'' \u2013 as a derogatory [[epithet]] for an exceedingly subservient person, particularly one aware of their own lower-class racial status.\n\n==Original characterization and critical evaluations==\nAt the time of the novel's initial publication in 1851, Uncle Tom was a rejection of the existing stereotypes of [[minstrel show]]s; Stowe's melodramatic story humanized the suffering of slavery for white audiences by portraying Tom as a Jesus-like figure who is ultimately martyred, beaten to death by a cruel master because he refuses to betray the whereabouts of two women who had escaped from slavery.<ref name=\"williams\" /><ref name=\"parfait\">{{cite book |last=Parfait |first=Claire |year=2007 |title=The publishing history of Uncle Tom's cabin, 1852\u20132002 |publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd. |isbn=978-0-7546-5514-5 |pages=1\u20132, 6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J-IaLbTxpVYC&pg=PA1&dq=Uncle+Tom&ei=T5zmSYC9GoOIzQTwnJTBCA |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref> Stowe reversed the gender conventions of slave narratives by juxtaposing Uncle Tom's passivity against the daring of three [[African American]] women who escape from slavery.<ref name=\"williams\" />\n\nThe novel was both influential and commercially successful, published as a serial from 1851 to 1852 and as a book from 1852 onward.<ref name=\"williams\" /><ref name=\"parfait\" /> An estimated 500,000 copies had sold worldwide by 1853, including unauthorized reprints.<ref name=\"meer\">{{cite book |last=Meer |first=Sarah |year=2005 |title=Uncle Tom mania: slavery, minstrelsy, and transatlantic culture in the 1850s |publisher=University of Georgia Press |isbn=978-0-8203-2737-2 |pages=1\u20134, 9, 14\u201315 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rKu7Tp8_-6wC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Uncle+Tom |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref> Senator [[Charles Sumner]] credited ''Uncle Tom's Cabin'' for the election of [[Abraham Lincoln]], an opinion that is later echoed in the apocryphal story of Lincoln greeting Stowe with the quip \"So you're the little woman who wrote the book that made this great war!\" (see [[American Civil War]]).<ref name=\"williams\" /><ref>{{Cite journal |last=R. |first=Vollaro, Daniel |date=2009-01-01 |title=Lincoln, Stowe, and the 'Little Woman/Great War' Story: The Making, and Breaking, of a Great American Anecdote |url=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/j/jala/2629860.0030.104/--lincoln-stowe-and-the-little-womangreat-war-story-the-making?rgn=main;view=fulltext |journal=Journal of the Abraham Lincoln Association |language=en |volume=30|issue=1|issn=1945-7987}}</ref> [[Frederick Douglass]] praised the novel as \"a flash to light a million camp fires in front of the embattled hosts of slavery\".<ref name=\"williams\" /> Despite Douglass's enthusiasm, an anonymous 1852 reviewer for [[William Lloyd Garrison]]'s publication ''The Liberator'' suspected a racial double standard in the idealization of Uncle Tom:\n\n<blockquote>Uncle Tom's character is sketched with great power and rare religious perception. It triumphantly exemplifies the nature, tendency, and results of Christian non-resistance. We are curious to know whether Mrs. Stowe is a believer in the duty of non-resistance for the White man, under all possible outrage and peril, as for the Black man ... [For whites in parallel circumstances, it is often said] Talk not of overcoming evil with good\u2014it is madness! Talk not of peacefully submitting to chains and stripes\u2014it is base servility! Talk not of servants being obedient to their masters\u2014let the blood of tyrants flow! How is this to be explained or reconciled? Is there one law of submission and non-resistance for the Black man, and another of rebellion and conflict for the white man? When it is the whites who are trodden in the dust, does Christ justify them in taking up arms to vindicate their rights? And when it is the blacks who are thus treated, does Christ require them to be patient, harmless, long-suffering, and forgiving? Are there two Christs?<ref name=\"liberator\">{{cite book |author=<!--anonymous--> |year=2004 |origyear=1852 |title=Untitled review, republished in A Routledge literary sourcebook on Harriet Beecher Stowe's Uncle Tom's cabin by Debra J. Rosenthal |publisher=<!--William Lloyd Garrison (original publisher)-->Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-23473-3 |page=35 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eptkDlB3J4kC&pg=PA1&dq=Uncle+Tom |accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[James Weldon Johnson]], a prominent figure of the [[Harlem Renaissance]], expresses an  antipathetic opinion in his autobiography:\n\n<blockquote>For my part, I was never an admirer of Uncle Tom, nor of his type of goodness; but I believe that there were lots of old Negroes as foolishly good as he.</blockquote>\n\nIn 1949, American writer [[James Baldwin (writer)|James Baldwin]] rejected the [[emasculation]] of the title character \"robbed of his humanity and divested of his sex\" as the price of spiritual salvation for a dark-skinned man in a fiction whose African-American characters, in Baldwin's view, were invariably two dimensional stereotypes.<ref name=\"williams\" /><ref name=\"baldwin\">{{cite book |last=Baldwin |first=James |date=2006 |origyear=1949 |title=Everybody's Protest Novel (partial republication) |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=978-0-674-02352-9 |pages=118\u2013121 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1loJe4UmHPAC&pg=PA118&dq=James+Baldwin+Uncle+Tom |accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref> To Baldwin, Stowe was closer to a pamphleteer than a novelist and her artistic vision was fatally marred by polemics and racism that manifested especially in her handling of the title character.<ref name=\"baldwin\" /> Stowe had stated that her sons had wept when she first read them the scene of Uncle Tom's death, but after Baldwin's essay it ceased being respectable to accept the melodrama of the Uncle Tom story.<ref name=\"williams\" /> Uncle Tom became what critic Linda Williams describes as \"an epithet of servility\" and the novel's reputation plummeted until feminist critics led by [[Jane Tompkins]] reassessed the tale's female characters.<ref name=\"williams\" />\n\nAccording to Debra J. Rosenthal, in an introduction to a collection of critical appraisals for the ''Routledge Literary Sourcebook on Harriet Beecher Stowe's Uncle Tom's Cabin'', overall reactions have been mixed with some critics praising the novel for affirming the humanity of the African American characters and for the risks Stowe assumed in taking a very public stand against slavery before abolitionism had become a socially acceptable cause, and others criticizing the very limited terms upon which those characters' humanity was affirmed and the artistic shortcomings of political melodrama.<ref name=\"rosenthal\">{{cite book |last=Rosenthal |first=Debra J. |year=2004 |title=A Routledge literary sourcebook on Harriet Beecher Stowe's Uncle Tom's cabin |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-23473-3 |pages=30\u201331 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eptkDlB3J4kC&pg=PA1&dq=Uncle+Tom |accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Inspiration==\n[[File:Uncle Tom and Eva, Staffordshire, England, 1855-1860, glazed and painted ceramic - Concord Museum - Concord, MA - DSC05597.JPG|thumb|''Uncle Tom and Eva'', [[Staffordshire figure]], England, 1855\u20131860, glazed and painted [[earthenware]]]]\nA specific impetus for the novel was the [[Fugitive Slave Act of 1850]], which imposed heavy fines upon law enforcement personnel in Northern states if they refused to assist the return of people who escaped from slavery.<ref name=\"parfait\" /><ref name=\"law\">{{cite web |title=The Fugitive Slave Act |publisher=U.S. Constitution Online |url=http://www.usconstitution.net/fslave.html |accessdate=2008-10-03}}</ref> The new law also stripped African Americans of the right to request a jury trial or to testify on their own behalf, even if they were legally free, whenever a single claimant presented an [[affidavit]] of ownership.<ref name=\"law\" /> The same law authorized a $1000 fine and six months imprisonment for anyone who knowingly harbored or assisted a fugitive slave.<ref name=\"law\" /> These terms infuriated Stowe, so the novel was written, read, and debated as a political [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]] tract.<ref name=\"parfait\" />\n\nStowe drew inspiration for the Uncle Tom character from several sources. The best-known of these was [[Josiah Henson]], an ex-slave whose autobiography, ''[[The Life of Josiah Henson, Formerly a Slave, Now an Inhabitant of Canada, as Narrated by Himself]]'', was originally published in 1849 and later republished in two extensively revised editions after the publication of ''Uncle Tom's Cabin''.<ref name=\"winks\">{{cite book |last=Winks |first=Robin W. |year=2003 |title=Autobiography of Josiah Henson: An Inspiration for Harriet Beecher Stowe's Uncle Tom (introduction) |publisher=Courier Dover Publications |isbn=978-0-486-42863-5 |pages=v\u2013vi, x\u2013xi, xviii\u2013xix |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bCYuNTzua2cC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Uncle+Tom&ei=T5zmSYC9GoOIzQTwnJTBCA |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref> Henson was enslaved at birth in 1789.<ref name=\"winks\" /> He became a Christian at age eighteen and began preaching.<ref name=\"winks\" /> Henson attempted to purchase his freedom for $450, but after selling his personal assets to raise $350 and signing a promissory note for the remainder Henson's owner raised the price to $1000; Henson was unable to prove that the original agreement had been for a lesser amount.<ref name=\"winks\" /> Shortly afterward Henson was ordered on a trip south to [[New Orleans]]. When he learned that he was to be sold there, he obtained a weapon. He contemplated murdering his white companions with the weapon, but decided against violence because his Christian morals forbade it.<ref name=\"winks\" /> A sudden illness in one of his companions forced their return to [[Kentucky]], and shortly afterward Henson escaped north with his family, settling in Canada where he became a civic leader.<ref name=\"winks\" />\n\nStowe read the first edition of Henson's narrative and later confirmed that she had incorporated elements from it into ''Uncle Tom's Cabin''.<ref name=\"winks\" /> Kentucky and New Orleans figure in both Henson's narrative and the novel's settings, and some other story elements are similar.<ref name=\"winks\" />\n\nIn the public imagination, however, Henson became synonymous with Uncle Tom.<ref name=\"winks\" /> After Stowe's death her son and grandson claimed she and Henson had met before ''Uncle Tom's Cabin'' was written, but the chronology does not hold up to scrutiny and she probably drew material only from his published autobiography.<ref name=\"winks\" />\n\n==Epithet==\nIn short terms, Uncle Tom is labeled to persons, similar to ''snitch'' or ''betrayer'', whose motive is driven by acceptance that doing slavery was just how the (antebellum) Southern society worked, whether the acceptance is spontaneous or coerced.\n\nThe term \"Uncle Tom\" is used as a derogatory [[epithet]] for an excessively subservient person, particularly when that person perceives their own lower-class status based on race. It is similarly used to negatively describe a person who betrays their own group by participating in its oppression, whether or not they do so willingly.<ref name=\"merriam-webster.com\" /><ref name=\"Uncle Tom\">[http://wordnetweb.princeton.edu/perl/webwn?o2=&o0=1&o7=&o5=&o1=1&o6=&o4=&o3=&s=uncle+tom&i=0&h=00#c \"Uncle Tom\"]. Wordnet.princeton.edu. Retrieved April 24, 2009.</ref>  The term has also, with more intended neutrality, been applied in psychology in the form \"[[Uncle Tom syndrome]]\", a term for the use of subservience, appeasement and passivity to cope with intimidation and threats.\n\nThe popular negative connotations of \"Uncle Tom\" have largely been attributed to the numerous derivative works inspired by ''Uncle Tom's Cabin'' in the decade after its release, rather than the original novel itself, whose title character is a more positive figure.<ref name=\"williams\">{{cite book |last=Williams |first=Linda |year=2002 |title=Playing the Race Card: Melodramas of Black and White from Uncle Tom to O.J. Simpson |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=978-0-691-10283-2 |pages=7, 30\u201331, 47\u201362 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VplfOW4Gch4C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Uncle+Tom&ei=T5zmSYC9GoOIzQTwnJTBCA |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref> These works lampooned and distorted the portrayal of Uncle Tom with politically loaded overtones.<ref name=\"meer\" />\n\n===History===\n[[File:Legree.png|thumb|250px|Uncle Tom, from an 1885 [[magic lantern]] series.]]\nAmerican copyright law before 1856 did not give novel authors any control over derivative stage adaptations, so Stowe neither approved the adaptations nor profited from them.<ref name=\"morgan\">{{cite book |last=Morgan |first=Jo-Ann |year=2007 |title=Uncle Tom's cabin as visual culture |publisher=University of Missouri Press |isbn=978-0-8262-1715-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/uncletomscabinas00morg/page/1 1]\u20135, 11\u201312, 17\u201319 |url=https://archive.org/details/uncletomscabinas00morg |url-access=registration |quote=James Baldwin Uncle Tom. |accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref> [[Minstrel show]] retellings in particular, usually performed by white men in [[blackface]], tended to be derisive and [[pro-slavery]], transforming Uncle Tom from Christian martyr to a [[fool (stock character)|fool]] or an [[apologist]] for slavery.<ref name=\"meer\" />\n\nAdapted theatrical performances of the novel, called [[Tom Shows]], remained in continual production in the United States for at least 80 years.<ref name=\"morgan\" /> These representations had a lasting cultural impact and influenced the pejorative nature of the term ''Uncle Tom'' in later popular use.<ref name=\"meer\" />\n\nAlthough not all minstrel depictions of Uncle Tom were negative, the dominant version developed into a stock character very different from Stowe's hero.<ref name=\"meer\" /><ref name=\"richardson\">{{cite book |last=Richardson |first=Rich\u00e9 |year=2007 |title=Black masculinity and the U.S. South: from Uncle Tom to gangsta |publisher=University of Georgia Press |isbn=978-0-8203-2890-4 |page=3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IlcS25xYsC4C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Uncle+Tom&ei=T5zmSYC9GoOIzQTwnJTBCA |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref> Stowe's Uncle Tom was a muscular and virile man who refused to obey when ordered to beat other slaves; the stock character of minstrel shows became a shuffling [[asexuality|asexual]] individual with a receding hairline and graying hair.<ref name=\"richardson\" />  To Jo-Ann Morgan, author of ''Uncle Tom's Cabin as Visual Culture'', these shifting representations undermined the subversive layers of Stowe's original characterization by redefining Uncle Tom until he fit within prevailing racist norms.<ref name=\"morgan\" /> Particularly after the Civil War, as the political thrust of the novel which had arguably helped to precipitate that war became obsolete to actual political discourse, popular depictions of the title character recast him within the apologetics of the [[Lost Cause of the Confederacy]].<ref name=\"morgan\" /> The virile father of the abolitionist serial and first book edition degenerated into a decrepit old man, and with that transformation the character lost the capacity for resistance that had originally given meaning to his choices.<ref name=\"morgan\" /><ref name=\"richardson\" /> Stowe never meant Uncle Tom to be a derided name, but the term as a pejorative has developed based on how later versions of the character, stripped of his strength, were depicted on stage.<ref name=NPR>{{cite news |last=Keyes |first=Allison |date=2002-11-29 |title=NPR: A New Look at 'Uncle Tom's Cabin' |work=[[The Tavis Smiley Show]] |publisher=[[National Public Radio|NPR]] |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=860450 |accessdate=2008-01-09}}</ref>\n\nClaire Parfait, author of ''The Publishing History of Uncle Tom's Cabin, 1852\u20132002'', opines that \"the many alterations in retellings of the Uncle Tom story demonstrate an impulse to correct the retellers' perceptions of its flaws\" and \"the capacity of the novel to irritate and rankle, even a century and a half after its first publication\".<ref name=\"parfait\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Acting white]]\n* [[List of In Living Color sketches#B|The Brothers Brothers]]\n* [[House Negro]]\n* [[Jump Jim Crow]]\n* [[List of ethnic slurs]]\n* [[Race traitor]]\n* [[Respectability politics]]\n* [[Shoneen]]\n* [[Stepin Fetchit]]\n* [[Sycophant]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Osofsky |editor-first=Gilbert |year=1969 |title=Puttin' On Ole Massa: The Slave Narratives of Henry Bibb, William Wells Brown, and Solomon Northup |publisher=[[Harper & Row]] |isbn=978-0-06-131432-2}}\n*{{cite video |people=Mohammad Ali |title=Thrilla in Manilla |medium=Documentary |publisher=HBO |location=USA |date=2009}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|Uncle Tom}}\n*[http://www.ferris.edu/news/jimcrow/tom/ An article on the Uncle Tom caricature]\n*[http://www.coverart.com/2011/11/every-girls-september-1931-the-real-uncle-tom/ An article from EveryGirls 1931 by Olive Burns Kirby]\n\n{{Uncle Tom's Cabin}}\n{{Slave narrative}}\n{{Ethnic slurs}}\n{{African American caricatures and stereotypes}}\n\n[[Category:African-American culture]]\n[[Category:American culture]]\n[[Category:American slang]]\n[[Category:Uncle Tom's Cabin]]\n[[Category:Anti-African and anti-black slurs]]\n[[Category:Characters in American novels of the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1852]]\n[[Category:Fictional slaves]]\n[[Category:Pejorative terms for people]]\n[[Category:Stereotypes of African Americans]]\n[[Category:Black people in literature]]\n[[Category:Male characters in literature]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Title character of Uncle Tom's Cabin}}\n{{Infobox character\n| series             = [[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]\n| image              = ElizaEngraving cropped.jpg\n| caption            = Detail of an illustration from the first book edition of ''Uncle Tom's Cabin'', depicting Uncle Tom as young and muscular\n| first              = ''Uncle Tom's Cabin''\n| last               = ''Uncle Tom's Cabin''\n| creator            = [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]]\n| gender             = Male\n| nationality        = American\n}}\n{{Slavery}}\n'''Uncle Tom''' is the title character of [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]]'s 1852 novel, ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]''.<ref name=\"merriam-webster.com\">{{MerriamWebsterDictionary|Uncle Tom}}</ref> The character was seen by many readers as ground-breaking humanistic portrayal of an African-American slave, one who uses non-resistance and gives his life to protect others who have escaped from slavery. However, the character also came to be seen \u2013 especially based on his portrayal in pro-slavery dramatizations \u2013 as inappropriately subservient to white slaveholders. This led to the use of ''Uncle Tom'' \u2013 often shortened to just ''Tom'' \u2013 as a derogatory [[epithet]] for an exceedingly subservient person, particularly one aware of their own lower-class status based on race.\n\n==Original characterization and critical evaluations==\nAt the time of the novel's initial publication in 1851, Uncle Tom was a rejection of the existing stereotypes of [[minstrel show]]s; Stowe's melodramatic story humanized the suffering of slavery for white audiences by portraying Tom as a Jesus-like figure who is ultimately martyred, beaten to death by a cruel master because he refuses to betray the whereabouts of two women who had escaped from slavery.<ref name=\"williams\" /><ref name=\"parfait\">{{cite book |last=Parfait |first=Claire |year=2007 |title=The publishing history of Uncle Tom's cabin, 1852\u20132002 |publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd. |isbn=978-0-7546-5514-5 |pages=1\u20132, 6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J-IaLbTxpVYC&pg=PA1&dq=Uncle+Tom&ei=T5zmSYC9GoOIzQTwnJTBCA |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref> Stowe reversed the gender conventions of slave narratives by juxtaposing Uncle Tom's passivity against the daring of three [[African American]] women who escape from slavery.<ref name=\"williams\" />\n\nThe novel was both influential and commercially successful, published as a serial from 1851 to 1852 and as a book from 1852 onward.<ref name=\"williams\" /><ref name=\"parfait\" /> An estimated 500,000 copies had sold worldwide by 1853, including unauthorized reprints.<ref name=\"meer\">{{cite book |last=Meer |first=Sarah |year=2005 |title=Uncle Tom mania: slavery, minstrelsy, and transatlantic culture in the 1850s |publisher=University of Georgia Press |isbn=978-0-8203-2737-2 |pages=1\u20134, 9, 14\u201315 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rKu7Tp8_-6wC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Uncle+Tom |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref> Senator [[Charles Sumner]] credited ''Uncle Tom's Cabin'' for the election of [[Abraham Lincoln]], an opinion that is later echoed in the apocryphal story of Lincoln greeting Stowe with the quip \"So you're the little woman who wrote the book that made this great war!\" (see [[American Civil War]]).<ref name=\"williams\" /><ref>{{Cite journal |last=R. |first=Vollaro, Daniel |date=2009-01-01 |title=Lincoln, Stowe, and the 'Little Woman/Great War' Story: The Making, and Breaking, of a Great American Anecdote |url=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/j/jala/2629860.0030.104/--lincoln-stowe-and-the-little-womangreat-war-story-the-making?rgn=main;view=fulltext |journal=Journal of the Abraham Lincoln Association |language=en |volume=30|issue=1|issn=1945-7987}}</ref> [[Frederick Douglass]] praised the novel as \"a flash to light a million camp fires in front of the embattled hosts of slavery\".<ref name=\"williams\" /> Despite Douglass's enthusiasm, an anonymous 1852 reviewer for [[William Lloyd Garrison]]'s publication ''The Liberator'' suspected a racial double standard in the idealization of Uncle Tom:\n\n<blockquote>Uncle Tom's character is sketched with great power and rare religious perception. It triumphantly exemplifies the nature, tendency, and results of Christian non-resistance. We are curious to know whether Mrs. Stowe is a believer in the duty of non-resistance for the White man, under all possible outrage and peril, as for the Black man ... [For whites in parallel circumstances, it is often said] Talk not of overcoming evil with good\u2014it is madness! Talk not of peacefully submitting to chains and stripes\u2014it is base servility! Talk not of servants being obedient to their masters\u2014let the blood of tyrants flow! How is this to be explained or reconciled? Is there one law of submission and non-resistance for the Black man, and another of rebellion and conflict for the white man? When it is the whites who are trodden in the dust, does Christ justify them in taking up arms to vindicate their rights? And when it is the blacks who are thus treated, does Christ require them to be patient, harmless, long-suffering, and forgiving? Are there two Christs?<ref name=\"liberator\">{{cite book |author=<!--anonymous--> |year=2004 |origyear=1852 |title=Untitled review, republished in A Routledge literary sourcebook on Harriet Beecher Stowe's Uncle Tom's cabin by Debra J. Rosenthal |publisher=<!--William Lloyd Garrison (original publisher)-->Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-23473-3 |page=35 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eptkDlB3J4kC&pg=PA1&dq=Uncle+Tom |accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[James Weldon Johnson]], a prominent figure of the [[Harlem Renaissance]], expresses an  antipathetic opinion in his autobiography:\n\n<blockquote>For my part, I was never an admirer of Uncle Tom, nor of his type of goodness; but I believe that there were lots of old Negroes as foolishly good as he.</blockquote>\n\nIn 1949, American writer [[James Baldwin (writer)|James Baldwin]] rejected the [[emasculation]] of the title character \"robbed of his humanity and divested of his sex\" as the price of spiritual salvation for a dark-skinned man in a fiction whose African-American characters, in Baldwin's view, were invariably two dimensional stereotypes.<ref name=\"williams\" /><ref name=\"baldwin\">{{cite book |last=Baldwin |first=James |date=2006 |origyear=1949 |title=Everybody's Protest Novel (partial republication) |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=978-0-674-02352-9 |pages=118\u2013121 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1loJe4UmHPAC&pg=PA118&dq=James+Baldwin+Uncle+Tom |accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref> To Baldwin, Stowe was closer to a pamphleteer than a novelist and her artistic vision was fatally marred by polemics and racism that manifested especially in her handling of the title character.<ref name=\"baldwin\" /> Stowe had stated that her sons had wept when she first read them the scene of Uncle Tom's death, but after Baldwin's essay it ceased being respectable to accept the melodrama of the Uncle Tom story.<ref name=\"williams\" /> Uncle Tom became what critic Linda Williams describes as \"an epithet of servility\" and the novel's reputation plummeted until feminist critics led by [[Jane Tompkins]] reassessed the tale's female characters.<ref name=\"williams\" />\n\nAccording to Debra J. Rosenthal, in an introduction to a collection of critical appraisals for the ''Routledge Literary Sourcebook on Harriet Beecher Stowe's Uncle Tom's Cabin'', overall reactions have been mixed with some critics praising the novel for affirming the humanity of the African American characters and for the risks Stowe assumed in taking a very public stand against slavery before abolitionism had become a socially acceptable cause, and others criticizing the very limited terms upon which those characters' humanity was affirmed and the artistic shortcomings of political melodrama.<ref name=\"rosenthal\">{{cite book |last=Rosenthal |first=Debra J. |year=2004 |title=A Routledge literary sourcebook on Harriet Beecher Stowe's Uncle Tom's cabin |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-23473-3 |pages=30\u201331 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eptkDlB3J4kC&pg=PA1&dq=Uncle+Tom |accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Inspiration==\n[[File:Uncle Tom and Eva, Staffordshire, England, 1855-1860, glazed and painted ceramic - Concord Museum - Concord, MA - DSC05597.JPG|thumb|''Uncle Tom and Eva'', [[Staffordshire figure]], England, 1855\u20131860, glazed and painted [[earthenware]]]]\nA specific impetus for the novel was the [[Fugitive Slave Act of 1850]], which imposed heavy fines upon law enforcement personnel in Northern states if they refused to assist the return of people who escaped from slavery.<ref name=\"parfait\" /><ref name=\"law\">{{cite web |title=The Fugitive Slave Act |publisher=U.S. Constitution Online |url=http://www.usconstitution.net/fslave.html |accessdate=2008-10-03}}</ref> The new law also stripped African Americans of the right to request a jury trial or to testify on their own behalf, even if they were legally free, whenever a single claimant presented an [[affidavit]] of ownership.<ref name=\"law\" /> The same law authorized a $1000 fine and six months imprisonment for anyone who knowingly harbored or assisted a fugitive slave.<ref name=\"law\" /> These terms infuriated Stowe, so the novel was written, read, and debated as a political [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]] tract.<ref name=\"parfait\" />\n\nStowe drew inspiration for the Uncle Tom character from several sources. The best-known of these was [[Josiah Henson]], an ex-slave whose autobiography, ''[[The Life of Josiah Henson, Formerly a Slave, Now an Inhabitant of Canada, as Narrated by Himself]]'', was originally published in 1849 and later republished in two extensively revised editions after the publication of ''Uncle Tom's Cabin''.<ref name=\"winks\">{{cite book |last=Winks |first=Robin W. |year=2003 |title=Autobiography of Josiah Henson: An Inspiration for Harriet Beecher Stowe's Uncle Tom (introduction) |publisher=Courier Dover Publications |isbn=978-0-486-42863-5 |pages=v\u2013vi, x\u2013xi, xviii\u2013xix |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bCYuNTzua2cC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Uncle+Tom&ei=T5zmSYC9GoOIzQTwnJTBCA |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref> Henson was enslaved at birth in 1789.<ref name=\"winks\" /> He became a Christian at age eighteen and began preaching.<ref name=\"winks\" /> Henson attempted to purchase his freedom for $450, but after selling his personal assets to raise $350 and signing a promissory note for the remainder Henson's owner raised the price to $1000; Henson was unable to prove that the original agreement had been for a lesser amount.<ref name=\"winks\" /> Shortly afterward Henson was ordered on a trip south to [[New Orleans]]. When he learned that he was to be sold there, he obtained a weapon. He contemplated murdering his white companions with the weapon, but decided against violence because his Christian morals forbade it.<ref name=\"winks\" /> A sudden illness in one of his companions forced their return to [[Kentucky]], and shortly afterward Henson escaped north with his family, settling in Canada where he became a civic leader.<ref name=\"winks\" />\n\nStowe read the first edition of Henson's narrative and later confirmed that she had incorporated elements from it into ''Uncle Tom's Cabin''.<ref name=\"winks\" /> Kentucky and New Orleans figure in both Henson's narrative and the novel's settings, and some other story elements are similar.<ref name=\"winks\" />\n\nIn the public imagination, however, Henson became synonymous with Uncle Tom.<ref name=\"winks\" /> After Stowe's death her son and grandson claimed she and Henson had met before ''Uncle Tom's Cabin'' was written, but the chronology does not hold up to scrutiny and she probably drew material only from his published autobiography.<ref name=\"winks\" />\n\n==Epithet==\nIn short terms, Uncle Tom is labeled to persons, similar to ''snitch'' or ''betrayer'', whose motive is driven by acceptance that doing slavery was just how the (antebellum) Southern society worked, whether the acceptance is spontaneous or coerced.\n\nThe term \"Uncle Tom\" is used as a derogatory [[epithet]] for an excessively subservient person, particularly when that person perceives their own lower-class status based on race. It is similarly used to negatively describe a person who betrays their own group by participating in its oppression, whether or not they do so willingly.<ref name=\"merriam-webster.com\" /><ref name=\"Uncle Tom\">[http://wordnetweb.princeton.edu/perl/webwn?o2=&o0=1&o7=&o5=&o1=1&o6=&o4=&o3=&s=uncle+tom&i=0&h=00#c \"Uncle Tom\"]. Wordnet.princeton.edu. Retrieved April 24, 2009.</ref>  The term has also, with more intended neutrality, been applied in psychology in the form \"[[Uncle Tom syndrome]]\", a term for the use of subservience, appeasement and passivity to cope with intimidation and threats.\n\nThe popular negative connotations of \"Uncle Tom\" have largely been attributed to the numerous derivative works inspired by ''Uncle Tom's Cabin'' in the decade after its release, rather than the original novel itself, whose title character is a more positive figure.<ref name=\"williams\">{{cite book |last=Williams |first=Linda |year=2002 |title=Playing the Race Card: Melodramas of Black and White from Uncle Tom to O.J. Simpson |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=978-0-691-10283-2 |pages=7, 30\u201331, 47\u201362 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VplfOW4Gch4C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Uncle+Tom&ei=T5zmSYC9GoOIzQTwnJTBCA |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref> These works lampooned and distorted the portrayal of Uncle Tom with politically loaded overtones.<ref name=\"meer\" />\n\n===History===\n[[File:Legree.png|thumb|250px|Uncle Tom, from an 1885 [[magic lantern]] series.]]\nAmerican copyright law before 1856 did not give novel authors any control over derivative stage adaptations, so Stowe neither approved the adaptations nor profited from them.<ref name=\"morgan\">{{cite book |last=Morgan |first=Jo-Ann |year=2007 |title=Uncle Tom's cabin as visual culture |publisher=University of Missouri Press |isbn=978-0-8262-1715-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/uncletomscabinas00morg/page/1 1]\u20135, 11\u201312, 17\u201319 |url=https://archive.org/details/uncletomscabinas00morg |url-access=registration |quote=James Baldwin Uncle Tom. |accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref> [[Minstrel show]] retellings in particular, usually performed by white men in [[blackface]], tended to be derisive and [[pro-slavery]], transforming Uncle Tom from Christian martyr to a [[fool (stock character)|fool]] or an [[apologist]] for slavery.<ref name=\"meer\" />\n\nAdapted theatrical performances of the novel, called [[Tom Shows]], remained in continual production in the United States for at least 80 years.<ref name=\"morgan\" /> These representations had a lasting cultural impact and influenced the pejorative nature of the term ''Uncle Tom'' in later popular use.<ref name=\"meer\" />\n\nAlthough not all minstrel depictions of Uncle Tom were negative, the dominant version developed into a stock character very different from Stowe's hero.<ref name=\"meer\" /><ref name=\"richardson\">{{cite book |last=Richardson |first=Rich\u00e9 |year=2007 |title=Black masculinity and the U.S. South: from Uncle Tom to gangsta |publisher=University of Georgia Press |isbn=978-0-8203-2890-4 |page=3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IlcS25xYsC4C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Uncle+Tom&ei=T5zmSYC9GoOIzQTwnJTBCA |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref> Stowe's Uncle Tom was a muscular and virile man who refused to obey when ordered to beat other slaves; the stock character of minstrel shows became a shuffling [[asexuality|asexual]] individual with a receding hairline and graying hair.<ref name=\"richardson\" />  To Jo-Ann Morgan, author of ''Uncle Tom's Cabin as Visual Culture'', these shifting representations undermined the subversive layers of Stowe's original characterization by redefining Uncle Tom until he fit within prevailing racist norms.<ref name=\"morgan\" /> Particularly after the Civil War, as the political thrust of the novel which had arguably helped to precipitate that war became obsolete to actual political discourse, popular depictions of the title character recast him within the apologetics of the [[Lost Cause of the Confederacy]].<ref name=\"morgan\" /> The virile father of the abolitionist serial and first book edition degenerated into a decrepit old man, and with that transformation the character lost the capacity for resistance that had originally given meaning to his choices.<ref name=\"morgan\" /><ref name=\"richardson\" /> Stowe never meant Uncle Tom to be a derided name, but the term as a pejorative has developed based on how later versions of the character, stripped of his strength, were depicted on stage.<ref name=NPR>{{cite news |last=Keyes |first=Allison |date=2002-11-29 |title=NPR: A New Look at 'Uncle Tom's Cabin' |work=[[The Tavis Smiley Show]] |publisher=[[National Public Radio|NPR]] |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=860450 |accessdate=2008-01-09}}</ref>\n\nClaire Parfait, author of ''The Publishing History of Uncle Tom's Cabin, 1852\u20132002'', opines that \"the many alterations in retellings of the Uncle Tom story demonstrate an impulse to correct the retellers' perceptions of its flaws\" and \"the capacity of the novel to irritate and rankle, even a century and a half after its first publication\".<ref name=\"parfait\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Acting white]]\n* [[List of In Living Color sketches#B|The Brothers Brothers]]\n* [[House Negro]]\n* [[Jump Jim Crow]]\n* [[List of ethnic slurs]]\n* [[Race traitor]]\n* [[Respectability politics]]\n* [[Shoneen]]\n* [[Stepin Fetchit]]\n* [[Sycophant]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Osofsky |editor-first=Gilbert |year=1969 |title=Puttin' On Ole Massa: The Slave Narratives of Henry Bibb, William Wells Brown, and Solomon Northup |publisher=[[Harper & Row]] |isbn=978-0-06-131432-2}}\n*{{cite video |people=Mohammad Ali |title=Thrilla in Manilla |medium=Documentary |publisher=HBO |location=USA |date=2009}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|Uncle Tom}}\n*[http://www.ferris.edu/news/jimcrow/tom/ An article on the Uncle Tom caricature]\n*[http://www.coverart.com/2011/11/every-girls-september-1931-the-real-uncle-tom/ An article from EveryGirls 1931 by Olive Burns Kirby]\n\n{{Uncle Tom's Cabin}}\n{{Slave narrative}}\n{{Ethnic slurs}}\n{{African American caricatures and stereotypes}}\n\n[[Category:African-American culture]]\n[[Category:American culture]